<Group labelreference="L22" drawlabel="true">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">The Navier Stokes equations are not quite as much of a pain to write in other coordinate systems as the linear elasticity equations .  This is basically because vector operators can do a great deal of the work and the boundary conditions are  often no slip and hence don't involve the stress tensor.  Thus the Maple vector calculus package is very useful as a tool.  The basic task is to change the vector laplacian from the viscous terms and the material derivative to the coordinate system you want to use.  The former has a built in Maple function, while the latter uses a vector identity to rewrite the u dot grad u term in terms of the standard operators.</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
